description.text:
Edit: Added the model for the motor.

This is a motor mount for a Netrox 12V gearmotor (C9050 Smartmotor), or a similar motor. The Netrox is 25mm in diameter with two screw holes. The motor can be held in the mount with these two screws or with friction (you may need to shim it slightly with paper). The mount attaches to a surface at the two counterbored holes in the flat bar. It positions the motor's axis at 30mm from the mounting surface, which as the astute have no doubt determined, is big to permit wheels slightly under 60mm diameter.

There is a support bracket included that is meant to help hold the motor's axis perpendicular to the mounting surface. This simply encircles the motor; secure attachment is not necessary (you can also shim this piece if you like, such as to prevent rattling).

Also included are two optional motor mount guide plates (to mark the surface you want to attach the mount to with the centers of the screw holes). Use whichever of these you prefer.

description.text:
evolution of the previous version ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1205037 )
but with the following improvements.

  • 2:1 step down gear ratio for z stepper (2x torque to compensate for 1 less motor)
  • More adjust-ability in belt tension (3 motor mount positions, more range in fixed idlers and more adjustment for screw adjustable idler)
  • M8 rods to tie down top caps and the ability to triangulate to reduce X wobble.

For reference:
The M8 bolts joining the M8 connector blocks are M8x40.
The M8 rods are (I think) all 46cm long but you may wish to experiment with different lengths

suggestions:

  • I have not put an extra pair of m8 connector blocks half way up (where diagonal and vertical rods cross over) and this may improve x rigidity further)
  • Go slow when you print the M8 connector blocks, I had these pop off once due to the head hitting a curling overhang.

title: limited slip reel holder for the ultimaker 2 50mm reels

description.text:
This is my own design for a reel holder for the Ultimaker 2. It has 3 spring-loaded chucks that hold the reel firmly in place and a limited slip function that enables the holder to rotate smoothly but prevents unwanted unwinding.

I have designed this reel holder for filament spools with a 50mm centre hole. As I only have a Ultimaker at home I haven't been able to design more attachment plates for other printers but the parts are modular and easy to customize to fit onto other printers. Please send me some measurements for your printer and I will add the design to the library.

All the plastic parts are printed in PLA on my Ultimaker 2 with a brim at 0.15mm layer height, 1.2mm wall thickness, 50mm per second printspeed and 50% infill. Everything can be printed as is except for the attachment plate witch needs al little support under the lip.

To complete this project besides the printed parts you will also need:
2x 10mm of 2mm welding rod
6 pen springs
1 spring from a lighter ( BIC or any other flint operated lighter )
1 countersunk screw 3.5x30 axle attachment
4 countersunk screws 3x10 attachment plate/backplate
3 countersunk screws 3.5x25 outer body/inner body
3 pieces of binding wire +- 0.5 mm in diameter and roughly 10 cm long.

As for tools you will need:
a screwdriver ( matching your screws)
drill bit 2 mm
tough pliers to cut the welding rod and binding wire
a hobby knife
some sandpaper or file to smooth out the parts where necessary
axle grease

if you have any questions please let me know.

To make the reel holder you will have to print the following list of parts :
1 outer body
1 inner body core
1 axle
1 flange
1 attachment plate printer ( print with support under the lip )
1 base plate
2 wheel mounts you might want to print a spare because it is a very tiny part
2 wheels
3 chucks
3 spring plates chuck

When all your parts are finished printing, clean them up thoroughly and test fit the parts in their right place. Especially the three chucks as they will have to move freely even when you have screwed the core in place. I find that making a small chamfered edge as well as running the the parts gently down a piece of sandpaper or file makes for a very smooth spring loaded action. also make sure you take off the support from the attachment plate and test fit it to your printer. I ended up not sanding the underside of the big lip, but rather taking of a very small amount of material of the 2 side clips. their clamping function is not very important but breaking one of after you have finished building the reel holder is quiet a downer.
further points of interest before beginning assembly:
does the inner core fit into the outer body and can i get out again if I need to.
does the flange fit onto my outer body ( if you want to you can glue this part on or leave it loose)
does the inner core and outer body sub-assembly fit over the axle and rotate freely.
does the axle fit in the backplate.
will my screws fit! testfitting the screws is not a bad idea. and will make it easier to put everything together later on.

I use a brim when printing to keep my parts on the build plate. For adhesion I use no extra materials I print on the glass straight away, when you do this make sure your build plate is clean and free of fingerprints etc and that your parts cool well so they will come off easier.

lets start out with the chucks. To complete this sub-assembly you will need 1 chuck 1spring plate and 2 pen springs and one piece of binding wire. I scavenged 6 springs from old pens but the easiest way is to buy 6 identical pens to prevent difference in spring tension.
first press both ends of the binding wire through the bottom of the spring plate making sure both ends are roughly the same size. then take the springs and place one over each end of the wire. but first test fit the springs in the chuck as you might need to clean up the hole a bit to ensure smooth operation. chamfering the holes makes it easier for the springs to move freely in and out of the chuck.
then insert the binding wire through the small holes already present in the chuck. Depending on the settings of you printer you might need to open up these holes for the wire to go through. now place the spring plate on a flat surface and push down on the chuck until the springs are no longer visible and the chuck is touching the spring plate. Now bend over both ends of the binding wire and twist them together so they don't come loose during the rest of the assembly. repeat this process for the rest of the chucks.

now place the chucks in the outer body with the spring plates facing inwards. MAKE SURE YOU PLACE THE POINTED END OF THE CHUCKS UPWARDS!!! if you place them the wrong way you will tear the inner core in to pieces when you put the screws in place. With the chucks in place take the inner core and press it into the outer body. Move all the chucks around to verify they will move freely. Now you can use the 3 3,5x25 screws to attach the inner core and outer body together.
At this point you can unwind the wire from the chucks, ( I left mine in place so I wouldn't have to repeat the process of binding them if I needed to take these parts apart again )
If you choose to let them in, tape off the sharp ends of the wire a they will make your life difficult in the rest of the assembly.
if not cut off the twisted end from one side and with a pair of pliers pull on the other side until the wire comes out releasing the springs. The chucks should now have a nice spring loaded action to them. If not you have to take it apart again, smooth out your parts a little bit more, repeat the process of binding them and reassembling.
you can now lubricate the axle and press it into place. The grooves in the axle are their to keep the axle well lubricated.

You can now mate the attachment plate and backplate with the 4 3x10 screws. I oriented my wheels to be vertical when the reel holder is attached to my machine but the design allows you to rotate it to have the wheels horizontal. Start out with 2 screws and then add the other 2. Doing all at the same time might twist the parts to breaking point. the backplate and attachment plate should now be joint firmly flush with one another and without a gap in the middle.

You are now ready to fit the wheels and wheel mounts together. First take a 2mm drill-bit and very very gently clean up the holes in the wheel mounts for the spring and wheel axle ( welding wire ) also clean up the centre hole of the wheel itself here it is important to keep the hole concentric to the wheel so it will operate smoothly. Now take a slightly larger drill bit and clean up the holes for the spring a bit more so the lighter spring fits nicely. now take a pair of pliers and very gently cut the spring in two pieces of identical length. test fit the wheel mounts in the backplate with the springs in place. if they do not move freely use the file and sandpaper to clean up the wheel mount and the slide in the backplate. Store the springs in a safe place for now as they are very small and easy to loose.
now test fit the wheel on the welding wire. It has to move freely on the axle when assembled. If it still grips the welding wire just twist and slide it on the wire itself. this will enlarge the hole just enough. You could use a larger drill bit but I find that to much play on the wheels makes for a bad operating performance.
now it is time to make the axles for the wheels for this you cut 2 pieces of welding wire 10 mm long and round of the edges of the wire. This makes it easier to press them into place and prevents the very tiny wheelmount from cracking or breaking. Now take one of the axles ant gently press it into one side of the wheelmount then place the wheel in the middle of the wheelmount and gently press or tap the axle into place. when pressing the axle in place your wheelmount might have bend a bit so pressing the back of a hobby knife between the mount and the wheel gives you back a bit of clearance. If your wheel is moving freely roll it down a flat surface to wear it in a bit. it is also advisable to lubricate the wheel at this point so it will keep rolling smoothly.

Now comes the final assembly, lay the backplate/attachmentplate with the backplate facing upwards on a flat surface. Take some lubricant and put it in the holes for the wheelmounts. Now lubricate the ridges of the inner core and the wheelmounts. place the lighter springs in the holes and place the wheelmounts on top. test the action of the wheels for one final time ( be carefull not to press to hard as the attachmentplate is very unstable and not supported at one side ) place the flange on the backplate so that the outer body will still be able to slide in. position the body precisely over the backplate and gently press the axle into place. keep the body and backplate pressed together and check if it rotates well. If you hear something rattling inside or have a non smooth rotating function one of the wheelmounts might have come out of its place during assembly if this keeps happening shorten the springs or make the holes for the springs a bit bigger. if everything checks out put the 3.5x30mm screw into the last hole. Make sure to keep the axle from rotating when you do this, you might need the pliers or a vice to keep this from happening. Also make sure you don't let the body lift from the backplate as this might cause the wheelmounts to fall out of place.

If all of this is done you should have a working nicely rotating reel-holder
I hope this instruction has been useful. if you still have some questions please let me know and I will see if I can help.

This is an improved and lighter version of my first SkyTrak: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1033593

This multirotor design is intended as a framework, rather than a finalized product.

I had the ideal of building an airframe on tracks (like a camera rig) rather than on plates like most designs out there.

Cutting carbon fiber plates for a custom UAV is complicated and laborious. 3D printed multirotor airframes do not scale up well because plastic is too flexible.

The SkyTrak Lite solves both issues by building a UAV on a carbon fiber tube "backbone". The tubes are light weight, common and cheap. The 3D printed plastic parts simply serve as joints. Core "track" tubes are 10mm in diameter, spaced 60mm from each other. I chose this format because it is a common rail configuration used on some commercial airframes and gimbals, like Tarot and DYS. The arms are 16mm in diameter, which is also a common size.

The design philosophy behind the SkyTrak was to make it fully modular and customizable. You can create your own parts and attach them anywhere on the tracks. It's also easy to repair or modify. I created the SkyTrak so that any part can be removed without having to do a full tear-down.

Furthermore, I have invented an arm-folding mechanism that works better than most common clips or friction methods found in regular commercial airframes.

The SkyTrak Lite weighs about 450 g, including CF tubes, nuts and bolts. Total weight will vary depending on size and type of motor mounts used. I did not 3D print the motor mounts since CF and aluminium ones are pretty cheap and more reliable.

The reason the battery sticks out so far at the back is to offset the weight of the camera and gimbal at the front. With a lighter payload, it would be possible to mount the battery to the underside.

Assembly is pretty intuitive. I have included pictures that should help you understand how it's put together. Here is a list of the parts you will need to buy. Make sure that your rail tubes have a 1 mm wall thickness. The 0.5 mm ones are too fragile.

PARTS - For the motor mounts, I used iFlight universal motor mounts (http://www.aliexpress.com/item/Free-shipping-Tarot-M16-Flight-Seat-Motor-Mount-Orange-TL68B08-01-multicopter-multirotor-frame-kit-quadcopter/32315808262.html) but anything that clamps to a 16mm diameter tube will work.
2x SkyTrak_lite_arm_mount: 2x CF tubes 10x8x300mm, 4x M3 18mm socket screw, 4x M3 nuts, 4x M4 35mm socket screw, 4x M4 lock nuts, 4x 8/4mm washer, 4x 9/4.5mm washers.
4x SkyTrak_lite_arm_clamp: 4x CF tubes 16x14x180mm, 4x M3 28mm socket screw, 4x M3 lock nuts, 8x 8/4mm washers.
2x SkyTrak_lite_legs: nothing.
2x SkyTrak_lite_plate: 8x M3 8mm screws, 8x M3 nuts.
(Optional) SkyTrak_lite_battery_holder: 2x M3 8mm screws, 2x M3 nuts.

The gimbal mount was made to fit the FeiyuTech 3D Mini3D.

Here are six triangular tiles each of which contains two half owls and half a guitar. The tiles are best printed directly on the build platform.  
Some possible exercises:  
Find one of the 4 solutions containing 6 complete owls.  
Find one of the 12 solutions containing 3 complete guitars and 3 complete owls.  
Find the 2 solutions where the 6 unmatched numerals at the outer edges of the hexagon sum to 30.  The sum from the example given above is 17.

description.text:
Simple Smooth Spool Skates

Instructions

  1. Print 4 copies of the object.
  2. Get 4 bearings. ("608" skate bearings. The most common bearing size is the “608.” Characterized by an 8mm core, a 22mm outer diameter and a 7mm width, these bearings are the industry standard and match up with nearly every skate wheel out there. They can be found in any skate shop and supercheap on ebay.)
  3. Put it together using friction fit. (if you have a calibrated printer or use 4pcs of 20mm M3 screws and nylon nuts. Print some washers if you wanna be fancy. I used some messed up prints. Looks awesome.)

I made some small improvements to a brilliant design by makecoolthings.The reason I made this was that I didn't understand why there had to be two parts when you can go by with one?

  • Instead of printing diffrent objects, you only print the same object. Check out the original object and you will understand.

Triceratops is a genus of herbivorous ceratopsid dinosaur that first appeared during the late Maastrichtian stage of the late Cretaceous period, about 68 million years ago (mya) in what is now North America. It is one of the last known non-avian dinosaur genera, and became extinct in the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event 66 million years ago.[1] The term Triceratops, which literally means "three-horned face", is derived from the Greek τρί- (tri-) meaning "three", κέρας (kéras) meaning "horn", and ὤψ (ops) meaning "face".

Bearing a large bony frill and three horns on its large four-legged body, and possessing similarities with the modern rhinoceros, Triceratops is one of the most recognizable of all dinosaurs and the best known ceratopsid. It shared the landscape with and was probably preyed upon by Tyrannosaurus, though it is less certain that the two did battle in the manner often depicted in traditional museum displays and popular images.

The exact placement of the Triceratops genus within the ceratopsid group has been debated by paleontologists. Two species, T. horridus and T. prorsus, are considered valid, although many other species have been named. Research published in 2010 suggested that the contemporaneous Torosaurus, a ceratopsid long regarded as a separate genus, represents Triceratops in its mature form. The view was immediately disputed and examination of more fossil evidence is expected to settle the debate.

Triceratops has been documented by numerous remains collected since the genus was first described in 1889, including at least one complete individual skeleton. Paleontologist John Scannella observed: "It is hard to walk out into the Hell Creek Formation and not stumble upon a Triceratops weathering out of a hillside." Forty-seven complete or partial skulls were discovered in just that area from 2000 to 2010. Specimens representing life stages from hatchling to adult have been found.

The functions of the frills and three distinctive facial horns on its head have long inspired debate. Traditionally, these have been viewed as defensive weapons against predators. More recent theories, noting the presence of blood vessels in the skull bones of ceratopsids, find it more probable that these features were primarily used in identification, courtship and dominance displays, much like the antlers and horns of modern reindeer, mountain goats, or rhinoceros beetles. The theory would find additional support if Torosaurus was found to be the mature form of Triceratops, as this would mean the frill also developed holes (fenestrae) as individuals reached maturity, rendering the structure more useful for display than defense.
